We are given that labour costs \textbackslash{}\$108 per unit and
capital costs \textbackslash{}\$2 per unit, and we want to minimize
cost. Thus the objective function is

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle C(x, y) = 108x + 2y.
\end{align*} The firm wants to produce 600
units, so using the production function we want
$\displaystyle 5x^{2/3}y^{1/3} = 600$. Thus the constraint function is

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle g(x, y) = x^{2/3}y^{1/3} - 120,
\end{align*} and the constraint is
g(x, y) = 0.

The Lagrange multiplier method says that the gradients of the objective
function and the constraint function should be proportional, or

\begin{align*}
\nabla C(x, y) = \lambda \nabla g(x, y).
\end{align*} The gradient of the
objective function is

\begin{align*}
\nabla C(x, y) = \langle 108, 2 \rangle.
\end{align*} and the gradient of the
constraint function is

\begin{align*}
\nabla g(x, y) = \langle \frac{2}{3}x^{-1/3}y^{1/3}, \frac{1}{3}x^{2/3}y^{-2/3}\rangle
\end{align*}
Then we have three equations that must be satisfied

\begin{align*}
108 = \lambda\frac{2}{3}x^{-1/3}y^{1/3},
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
2 = \lambda\frac{1}{3}x^{2/3}y^{-2/3},
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle x^{2/3}y^{1/3} - 120 = 0.
\end{align*}

Solving the second equation for $\lambda$ gives

\begin{align*}
\lambda = 6x^{-2/3}y^{2/3},
\end{align*} and substituting into the first equation
to eliminate $\lambda$ gives

\begin{align*}
108 = 6x^{-2/3}y^{2/3}\frac{2}{3}x^{-1/3}y^{1/3}.
\end{align*} Simplifying, we
have

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle 108 = 4x^{-1}y,
\end{align*} and then we solve for y to get

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle y = 27x.
\end{align*} Now substituting into the third equation, the
constraint equation, gives

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle x^{2/3}(27x)^{1/3} - 120 = 0.
\end{align*} Simplifying, we have

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle 3x = 120,
\end{align*} and thus

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle x = 40.
\end{align*} We then have that

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}y=27x=27(40)=1080.
\end{align*}

Therefore the cost is minimized when using 40 units of labour and 1080
units of capital.
